{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629271"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:04:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:04:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17261"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17261"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9951"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78053"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9951"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17261"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63475"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7646"},{"type":"tags","id":"10718"},{"type":"tags","id":"10719"},{"type":"tags","id":"10720"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23336"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78053"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring meiosis, paired chromosomes separate to form gametes in a process that follows Mendel\u0027s first law of inheritance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the law of segregation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Each parent contributes one randomly selected allele to offspring","Genes on the same chromosome are inherited together","Alleles of different genes assort independently","Traits blend together in offspring","Dominant alleles always mask recessive alleles"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMendel\u0027s first law of inheritance describes how \u003Cstrong\u003Eeach parent contributes one randomly selected allele to offspring\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs through meiosis, where homologous chromosomes separate into different gametes. When fertilisation occurs, the offspring inherits one allele from each parent\u0027s gamete, restoring the paired condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent different genetic concepts:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenes on the same chromosome are inherited together\u003C/strong\u003E describes genetic linkage, though this association can be disrupted by crossing over during meiosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlleles of different genes assort independently\u003C/strong\u003E refers to Mendel\u0027s second law (the Law of Independent Assortment), which explains how different genes are inherited separately from each other\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETraits blend together in offspring\u003C/strong\u003E represents an outdated theory that Mendel\u0027s work disproved by showing that traits remain distinct across generations\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDominant alleles always mask recessive alleles\u003C/strong\u003E describes the concept of dominance relationships between alleles, not how they are inherited\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe law of segregation forms the basis for understanding how genetic traits are passed from generation to generation while maintaining variation within populations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mendel\u0027s first law (law of segregation) states that each parent passes one randomly selected allele from each gene pair to offspring.","During meiosis, homologous chromosomes separate so that each gamete receives only one allele of each gene.","The law of segregation explains why offspring inherit one allele from each parent, maintaining genetic diversity."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Stenseth NC, Andersson L, Hoekstra HE. Gregor Johann Mendel and the development of modern evolutionary biology. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2022 Jul 26;119(30):e2201327119. doi:10.1073/pnas.2201327119. Epub 2022 Jul 18. PMID: 35858454; PMCID: PMC9335310."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63475"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17261"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63475"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T11:40:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T11:41:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9951"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78053"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","